.","Americanized form of German <b>Sellmann</b> (see   Sellman  )."]},{"name":"Seelye","meanings":["English: variant of   Seeley  ."]},{"name":"Sealy","meanings":["English: variant of   Seeley  .","Welsh: from the male personal name <i>Selyf</i> or <i>Seleu</i>, medieval Welsh vernacular forms of   Solomon   which were replaced by that form in the Welsh Bible of 1588.","Irish: variant of   Shelley   (in counties Cork and Kerry); elsewhere of English or Welsh origin, as in 1 above and 2."]},{"name":"Sealey","meanings":["English: variant of   Seeley  ."]},{"name":"Seley","meanings":["English: variant of   Seeley  . This form of the surname is now rare in Britain."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":9,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Thomas Seeley was born about 1373, in England. He had at least 1 son. He died after 1400."},"et":{"about 1373–after 1400":"umbes 1373–pärast 1400","1393–1442":"1393–1442","1373–1400":"1373–1400","1400":"1400","1442":"1442","1373":"1373","1382":"1382","1393":"1393","about 1373":"umbes 1373","after 140